%I A397409 #40 Jul 19 2026 19:12:36
%S A397409 1,2,4,3,6,9,8,12,16,5,10,15,20,25,18,24,30,36,7,14,21,28,35,42,49,32,
%T A397409 40,48,56,64,27,45,54,63,72,81,50,60,70,80,90,100,11,22,33,44,55,66,
%U A397409 77,88,99,110,121,84,96,108,120,132,144,13,26,39,52,65,78,91,104,117,130,143,156,169
%N A397409 Irregular triangle read by rows: row n lists, in increasing order, the products n*k such that A033677(n*k) = n.
%C A397409 Row n contains the positive multiples n*k for which n is the smallest divisor of n*k such that n >= sqrt(n*k). This forces 1 <= k <= n, because n >= sqrt(n*k) implies n^2 >= n*k; i.e., k <= n; and k >= 1 by definition, since n*k is a positive multiple of n.
%C A397409 For n > 1 the length of row n is A062854(n) = A333995(n) + A010051(n) = A027424(n) - A027424(n-1); row 1 has length 1.
%C A397409 Every positive integer N occurs in exactly one row, namely the row A033677(N). Thus the rows partition the positive integers N according to the value of A033677(N). Thus, the entire sequence is a permutation of the positive integers.
%C A397409 The initial term of row n is D(n); i.e., the smallest primitive entry in column n of the triangular multiplication table. The last term of row n is always n^2, because A033677(n^2) = n.
%C A397409 This triangle is distinct from A075383 where the n-th row has always exactly n terms. Here, row n consists exactly of the products that first appear when passing from the (n-1) X (n-1) multiplication table to the n X n multiplication table. The row first terms agree with A075384 for n = 1..39, but first differ at n = 40, where the row initial term here is 880 while A075384(40) = 920.
%F A397409 Row n = {x: A033677(x) = n} in increasing order.
%F A397409 Equivalently, row n = {n*k: 1 <= k <= n, and A033677(n*k) = n} in increasing order.
%F A397409 The row initial term is D(n) = n*rho(n), where rho(n) = min{k >= 1: A033677(n*k) = n}.
%e A397409 The first rows are:
%e A397409   row 1: 1;
%e A397409   row 2: 2,  4;
%e A397409   row 3: 3,  6, 9;
%e A397409   row 4:     8, 12, 16;
%e A397409   row 5: 5, 10, 15, 20, 25;
%e A397409   row 6:        18, 24, 30, 36;
%e A397409   row 7: 7, 14, 21, 28, 35, 42, 49;
%e A397409   row 8:            32, 40, 48, 56, 64;
%e A397409   row 9:        27,     45, 54, 63, 72, 81;
%e A397409 For row 4, the product 4 = 4*1 is not listed because A033677(4) = 2, so 4 first appears in row 2. The products 8, 12, and 16 are listed because A033677(8) = A033677(12) = A033677(16) = 4. Hence 8 is the start of row 4.
%e A397409 For row 6, the products 6 = 6*1 and 12 = 6*2 are not listed because A033677(6) = 3 and A033677(12) = 4. The products 18, 24, 30, and 36 are listed because A033677(18) = A033677(24) = A033677(30) = A033677(36) = 6. Hence 18 is the start of row 6.
%t A397409 row[n_] := Select[n * Range[n], Function[x, Select[Divisors[x], # >= Sqrt[x] &, 1] == {n}]]; Table[row[n], {n, 1, 13}] // Flatten (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 27 2026 *)
%o A397409 (PARI) f(n) = my(d=divisors(n)); d[length(d)\2+1]; \\ A033677
%o A397409 row(n) = select(x->f(x)==n, vector(n, k, k*n)); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Jul 05 2026
